Wolverine. How incredibly smart!!! Here a wolverine is breaking through a trapdoor and stealing the bait used by @thelynxproject as part of a long term study of Lynx movement in interior Alaska. One of my favorite parts about my job is the long term collaborations that result as a part of it. It’s been fun to work with these guys trying to educate the public about what they do and the species in general and see cool things like this as well as be on the cutting edge of how science is using tools like social media to further their endeavors. Can’t wait to get out in the field with them again soon. If you want to learn more about Lynx make sure to check them out. Tag a friend you think should see this. 😂

I feel like I have the best possible job in the world, working with wildlife and wild places, trying to bring them to the collective attention while highlighting our commonality through appreciation of simple beauty in nature. On any given day my biggest threat is maybe having a bear charge me or say getting injured in the backcountry somehow. What you see here as a result is my version of that beauty, that truth.
I can’t fathom having to be scared for my life, or face the risk of assassination for bringing that truth forward while exercising my First Amendment rights. I am at a total loss thinking about Jamal Khashoggi, the journalist assassinated recently by Saudi Arabia in an operation that has essentially been condoned by the White House. I can’t stand by and watch this get swept under the rug because of falling oil prices, arms or nuclear deals. If we as a society championing freedom and democracy for all are willing to accept the assassination of journalists working for a free press, I am afraid to find out where we go from here. Freedom of Speech and Freedom of the Press, are in the first amendment because they are the foundations of a free and open society. Democracy.

I saw a post the other day with a journalist bagging on the “cliched” statement that “journalism gives voice to the voiceless”….In this particular case, it seems clear to me that is exactly what we as a community of journalists should be doing. I refuse to stand by and watch this all go away without trying to use this feed for the common good. @whitehouse your actions regarding the assassination of journalist Jamal Khashoggi are unacceptable and shameful. You’re not destroying our country, you’re destroying Democracy.
Wherever you’re reading this, if you believe in Democracy I urge you to click on the link in my bio to find a list of your congressmen and women (or pick one, you can even find your congressional leaders on social media). Write to them today to let them know what you think. @senatorenzi @liz.cheney @senjohnbarrasso

2.5 million acres and no roads or trails makes for a bit of a challenge finding wildlife like wolves and bears in Yukon-Charley Rivers National Preserve. Luckily we spent plenty of time watching their movements and found some great locations for our remote cameras.  This grizzly bear lived along the river ecosystem below our camp in Yukon-Charley Rivers. He looks pretty healthy now, just imagine how much weight he’ll pack on as fall starts to approach. Winter is right around the corner in the far north. I’ve partnered with the National Park Service (@nationalparkservice) and Alaska National Parks (@alaskanps) to help show folks a little bit of what might otherwise go unseen in the boreal forests of the far north. Click on the link in my bio to learn and see more. #commonground

Every family that we met on this trip seemed to talk about tradition. Wanting to get outside with their families and establish a tradition of getting out and enjoying nature with their kids hoping that they’ll want to do the same with theirs. I suppose I didn’t even realize it but that’s exactly what I was trying to do too. Trying to lay a foundation for a life spent seeking the excitement of the outdoors. What are your family traditions that involve the outdoors? How has it helped you and your family? I’d love to hear. With @nature_org celebrating public lands and family traditions in #Utah.#commonground

I asked @alaskanps biologist Mat Sorum why it’s important to study wolves in Alaska. He said "Wolves are the check and balance of the ecosystem. They prevent overpopulation of their prey thereby preventing dramatic declines as well. The modulation of prey abundance benefits both humans and wolves alike"
#commonground #publiclands @nationalparkservice

When we started talking about this project, we were pretty much told we were going to fail. “No way those wolves would tolerate your presence” pretty much seemed to be the consensus. As we found and watched them from a distance the first year, I couldn’t help but notice locations that would be incredible camera trap locations. First and foremost when setting a camera trap is to try and capture some kind of behavior. Something unique. Our cameras stayed in the field for 6 weeks. I asked Mat Sorum, biologist for @alaskanps after he collected the cameras “If the footage we got before we left was a 5, where do we stand now?” “10” He replied. 🐺 ••• This work wouldn’t be possible without the vision and support of people out there like you. If you’re interested in making a tax deductible donation to support field work like this shoot me a DM and I’ll let you know how you can help.

A cougar scares off a group of eagles feeding on an elk kill.…. Perhaps the best part of my job is the relationships that I get to form with the folks that I’ve worked with. @yellowstone_cougar_project has been one of the best groups of researchers I’ve had the pleasure of being around.  Dr. Dan Stahler, and (soon to be Dr.) Colby Anton @cobblestonetosandweasel have led a group of dedicated scientists and technicians with the goal of learning more about the cougars of @yellowstonenps northern range.  I helped iron out the kinks in their camera trapping operation in the beginning with the help of an @insidenatgeo grant, and now we just can’t quit talking about how much fun we had, as well as how these animals continue to amaze us.
#gratitude #cougars #cats #catsofinstagram #justwait #commonground #publiclands

“A rich ecological assemblage of native subarctic mammals thrives in the preserve’s diverse habitats. Dall’s sheep, moose, and two distinct caribou herds are found throughout the area. Fourteen species of furbearers inhabit the preserve, of which marten and lynx are the most economically valuable. Grizzly and black bears also occur throughout the preserve. Small mammals, including mice, voles, and shrews, are important in the food web. The hardy wood frog is the lone native amphibian. A climate characterized by seasonal extremes precludes the occurrence of reptiles.”- From the National Park Service page educating the public about Yukon-Charley Rivers Preserve in eastern interior Alaska. Learn more at the link in my bio. #publiclands #wildlife @alaskanps @nationalparkservice

🔊 on. | When I asked @alaskanps Jeff Rasic about why he thought Yukon-Charley Rivers National Preserve was such a special place, he said “Well, all ecosystems are important, but a unique thing about Yukon-Charley is that protected within this conservation unit is an entire (and large) watershed--the Charley River basin--along with a segment of the massive Yukon River, plus a wide range of upland and lowland settings in which there live a full complement of large and small mammals, birds, and fish, predators and prey. All the pieces are there, and largely functioning together as they have for millennia. There are a few chinks--declining king salmon populations come to mind--but this is really intact system and something not to be taken for granted.” 🐺 #commonground #publiclands #alaska #wild #wolves #puppies @nationalparkservice

Easily one of my favorite places in Utah. Recognized by the International Dark Sky Association as a gold-tier Dark Sky Park in 2015 Capitol Reef National Park is a wonderful place to introduce kids to the beauty of the night sky. I shot this on an assignment through some of the more out of the way spots with @nature_org celebrating the variety of public lands in Utah. If we don’t get our kids excited to unplug and be outside, who will become the next generation of stewards for these places and for what end? ________________________________________________ #darkskies #stars @nature_utah #instamood #commonground
